{
  "entries": [
    {
      "url": "https://grokipedia.com/page/Southwest_Airlines",
      "suggested_edit": "Update the 'Regulatory Scrutiny and Fines' section to reflect the latest development: On December 6, 2025, the Trump administration waived the remaining $11 million fine from the $140 million civil penalty imposed in 2023 for the 2022 holiday meltdown and discontinued the Department of Transportation lawsuit filed in January 2025 against Southwest for chronically delayed flights. This action was announced by the Transportation Department, now led by former airline lobbyist Secretary Sean Duffy.",
      "original_text": "On December 18, 2023, the DOT imposed a record $140 million civil penalty on Southwest—the largest in agency history—for its December 2022 scheduling meltdown, which canceled over 16,900 flights and stranded passengers due to failures in crew scheduling software and inadequate contingency planning. Southwest also reimbursed passengers over $600 million in refunds and reimbursements as part of the resolution."
    },
    {
      "url": "https://grokipedia.com/page/Southwest_Airlines",
      "suggested_edit": "In the same section, add: Additionally, the January 2025 DOT lawsuit for chronic delays was shut down as part of the Trump administration's actions.",
      "original_text": "In January 2025, the DOT filed a lawsuit against Southwest alleging chronic delays on two routes (Las Vegas to San Diego and Orlando to Aruba) exceeding federal tarmac delay rules, seeking civil penalties up to $37,377 per violation without admitting liability by the airline."
    },
    {
      "url": "https://grokipedia.com/page/X.com",
      "suggested_edit": "Add to the regulatory issues with EU section: Amid escalating tensions, on December 7, 2025, X terminated the European Commission’s advertising account. The EU had used a deceptive tactic in an ad by disguising a link as a video to artificially boost reach while promoting a fine announcement against X. X highlighted the irony, noting the EU's dormant ad account exploited the platform's ad composer.",
      "original_text": "On July 12, 2024, the European Commission issued preliminary findings that X breached DSA obligations, including deceptive practices with its paid blue checkmark verification system, which regulators claimed misled users about account authenticity, and insufficient assessments of risks like election interference and foreign disinformation."
    }
  ]
}
